<main class="container">
    <h1>Privacy Policy and Terms and Conditions</h1>
    <p>I. Introduction At Machu Picchu Inka Trek, our primary commitment is to respect and comply with all applicable legal and regulatory provisions. We recognize the importance of personal data and its protection, which is why we are committed to handling it in a way that complies with the law and fosters public trust and security.</p>
    <p>II. Purpose This Policy aims to inform the public about our commitment to protecting personal data and the guidelines under which we process it in the course of our business activities. It also provides information on how data subjects can exercise their rights under the Personal Data Protection Regulations.</p>
    <p>III. Scope This Policy applies to all personal data processing activities carried out by Machu Picchu Inka Trek. It is also applicable to individuals or companies that require the processing of personal data and are responsible for its management.</p>
    <p>IV. Definitions In this policy, capitalized terms have the following meanings:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Personal Data Protection Law: Refers to Law 29733 and its amendments.</li>
        <li>Regulations of the Personal Data Protection Law: Refers to Supreme Decree No. 003-2013-JUS and its amendments.</li>
        <li>Personal Data Bank: A structured set of personal data, whether automated or not, stored in different formats.</li>
        <li>Sensitive Data: Personal data that includes information about an individual's intimate aspects, such as biometric data, racial origin, political, religious, or philosophical opinions, among others.</li>
        <li>Personal Data Bank Manager: The person or entity responsible for processing personal data on behalf of the data bank owner.</li>
        <li>Personal Data Protection Regulations: Includes the Personal Data Protection Law, its Regulations, amendments, and other complementary regulations.</li>
        <li>Personal Data Subject: The natural person to whom the personal data belongs.</li>
        <li>Data Subject’s Consent: The free, specific, informed, and unequivocal expression of will through which the data subject agrees to the processing of their personal data.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>V. Guiding Principles Machu Picchu Inka Trek is committed to adhering to the following guiding principles established in the Personal Data Protection Regulations:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>Principle of Legality: The processing of personal data will be carried out in accordance with the law, avoiding fraudulent or unlawful means.</li>
        <li>Principle of Consent: The processing of personal data requires the data subject’s consent unless otherwise provided by law.</li>
        <li>Principle of Purpose: Personal data will be collected for a specific, explicit, and lawful purpose and will not be used for other purposes.</li>
        <li>Principle of Proportionality: The processing of personal data will be appropriate and relevant to the purpose for which it was collected.</li>
        <li>Principle of Quality: The personal data processed must be truthful, accurate, and updated whenever possible, according to the purpose for which it was collected.</li>
        <li>Principle of Security: Technical, organizational, and legal measures will be applied to ensure the security of personal data.</li>
        <li>Principle of Right to Redress: Data subjects will be ensured the ability to exercise their rights in case of any violation of the regulations.</li>
        <li>Principle of Adequate Protection Level: For the transfer of personal data to other countries, an equivalent level of protection to that established by the regulations or international standards will be ensured.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>VI. Purpose of Personal Data Processing At Machu Picchu Inka Trek, we process personal data of employees, customers, suppliers, and other relevant individuals in our operations. This is done in compliance with the purposes authorized by each data subject in the consent provided, in accordance with the exceptions established by the Personal Data Protection Regulations.</p>
    <p>The general purposes for which we process personal data are as follows:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>To fulfill obligations arising from contractual and non-contractual relationships with data subjects.</li>
        <li>To communicate commercial information about our business activities, goods, and services to our target audiences, with the prior consent of the data subject.</li>
        <li>To update or delete personal data when inaccuracies, omissions, or errors are detected or when the purpose for which they were collected has been fulfilled.</li>
        <li>To ensure proper storage and use of personal data through technical, organizational, and legal measures.</li>
        <li>To comply with our legal obligations as an employer under the Personal Data Protection Law.</li>
        <li>To conduct security risk monitoring activities, such as video surveillance or biometric registration.</li>
        <li>To carry out due diligence and business risk management activities.</li>
        <li>To transfer personal data to third parties with whom we have contractual relationships and who require such information to fulfill contracted services. In the case of international transfers, an adequate level of protection will be ensured.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>All these purposes are duly communicated to the data subjects and collected with their corresponding consent, unless there is a legal exception.</p>
    <p>VII. Consent Machu Picchu Inka Trek will require the free, prior, express, unequivocal, and informed consent of the data subject for the processing of their personal data, except in cases of legal exceptions. Consent will not be required when personal data comes from publicly accessible sources or non-public sources that have the data subject’s consent.</p>
    <p>VIII. Rights of Data Subjects Data subjects have the following rights under the Personal Data Protection Regulations:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>Right of Access and Information: The data subject has the right to know what personal data is processed, how it was collected, the purpose of processing, the existence of the data bank, and the identity of those responsible for processing.</li>
    </ol>
